# Backend NestJS Conventions

The backend is organized by layers, not by a `modules/<feature>` tree.

## Active Layout

- `src/presentation/`: Nest modules, controllers, guards, and feature tokens.
- `src/application/`: use cases and application orchestration.
- `src/domain/`: entities, domain errors, and pure business rules.
- `src/interfaces/`: repository and boundary contracts.
- `src/infrastructure/`: database, mail, and technical adapters.
- `src/shared/`: cross-feature backend helpers.

## Working Rules

- Add code in the existing feature subtree first instead of creating a new top-level architecture slice.
- Use `@src/*` imports inside the backend.
- Controllers stay thin and call use cases; they should not contain repository or SQL logic.
- Use case files follow the existing `*.usecase.ts` naming convention.
- Nest symbol tokens are declared in feature `*.tokens.ts` files under `src/presentation/**`.
- Repository ports and boundary interfaces live under `src/interfaces/**` and typically use the `I*.port.ts` naming pattern.
- Infrastructure adapters implement those ports and stay under `src/infrastructure/**`.
- When behavior changes, update or add focused tests for the touched use case or controller.
